taxonomy.title: Office of the Historian Subject Taxonomy of the History of U.S. Foreign Relations

description.p:
The Subject Taxonomy of the History of U.S. Foreign Relations is a hierarchical taxonomy that consists of categories and tags. The taxonomy is organized into ___ top-level categories:
Agreements and Mandates
Events
Organizations
People
Places
Topics Below these top-level categories are additional nested levels of categories and tags, becoming more specific at deeper levels.

collection.label: Agreements and Mandates
collection.definition: Proposed and implemented legislation, laws, directives, and charters as well as bilateral and multilateral agreements such as treaties.

collection.label: Organizations
collection.definition: Corporate bodies, non-governmental organizations, collectives, and other groups of persons that are identifiable by a particular name and may act as an entity.

collection.label: People
collection.definition: Contains lists of Presidents and Secretaries of State in chronological order.
collection.usage-hint: For people named in resources, only use a person tag if the resource is relevant to their service as President or Secretary.

collection.label: Presidents
collection.definition: Presidential administrations in chronological order. (P) is appended to a President's name in cases where the President also served as Secretary of State. A range of years is appended in cases where the President served in two non-consecutive administrations.

collection.label: Secretaries of State
collection.definition: Secretaries of State in chronological order. (S) is appended to a Secretary's name in cases where the Secretary also served as President. A range of years is appended in cases where the Secretary served non-consecutively.

collection.label: Places
collection.definition: Territories on today's map of the world, as classified by status and region by the Office of The Geographer and Global Issues, Bureau of Intelligence and Research, U.S. Department of State.
collection.source: The current Places list was taken from the factsheets Independent States in the World and Dependencies and Areas of Special Sovereignty, accessed online on June 25, 2019.

scopeNote.label: Note on Close and Exact Matches

collection.scopeNote:
Per the Federal Geographic Data Committee, “The GENC Standard specifies a profile of ISO 3166, Codes for the representation of names of countries and their subdivisions. This profile addresses unique U.S. Government requirements for: restrictions in recognition of the national sovereignty of a country; identification and recognition of geopolitical entities not included in ISO 3166; and use of names of countries and country subdivisions that have been approved by the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN).
“The US Government cannot use ISO 3166 directly. US Public Law 80-242 (1947) requires the US Government to use geographic names that have been approved by the BGN. ISO 3166 contains some country and subdivision names that vary from those approved by the BGN. The geopolitical entities included in ISO 3166 are those that are recognized by the United Nations (UN). The GENC Ed1.0 is the US Government implementation of ISO 3166-1 that conforms to BGN and US Government recognition policy.”
collection.authority: Office of The Geographer and Global Issues, Bureau of Intelligence and Research, U.S. Department of State, Washington, DC.

concept.scopeNote: Antarctica consists of the territory south of 60 degrees south latitude. This area includes claims by Argentina, Australia, Chile, France, New Zealand, Norway, and the United Kingdom, the legal status of which remains in suspense under the terms of the Antarctic Treaty of 1959. The United States recognizes no claims to Antarctica.
